>когда им ничего не досталось в руки...</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>when they got nothing in their hands...</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_ОЭ"/><biblScope>I 94</biblScope></bibl></cit><cit type="example" xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg type="dialect"><lang/></usg><quote>mʼarmi esti ku baftuja, wædta art nikkænʒinæn</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>если раздобуду чего-нибудь, то разведу огонь</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>if I get something, I'll start a fire</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_MSt."/><biblScope>10%l13%l</biblScope></bibl></cit><cit type="example" xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg type="dialect"><lang/></usg><quote>baʒorun æ armi ne ʽftujuj</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>позвать ей не удается („не дается в руки“)</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>she fails to call (‘not given in the hands’)</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_Bes._Ka_ke"/><biblScope>36</biblScope></bibl></cit></cit><cit type="exampleGroup" corresp="#sense_.2" n="2"><cit type="example"><quote>zærond ʒonyǧ wyd... je ʽrttæn ma se ʽrdǵytæ xawdæj læwwydysty zæxxyl, adæjmaǵy cænk˳yl kʼūxtaw</quote><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru"><q>сани были старые ... только половинки оглобель лежали еще упавшие на земле подобно обрубленным рукам человека</q></cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en"><q>the sled was old ... only the halves of the shaft lay still on the ground like the severed hands of a man</q></cit><bibl><ref target="#src_F."/><biblScope>1957 I 8</biblScope></bibl></cit></cit><note type="comment" xml:lang="">; </note><note type="comment" xml:lang="">; </note><etym xml:lang="ru">Как большинство анатомических терминов (см. <xr><ref target="#entry_aǧd"/><ref target="#entry_cong"/><ref target="#entry_fad"/><ref target="#entry_zæng"/><ref target="#entry_zonyg"/><ref target="#entry_bazyg"/><ref target="#entry_wæxsk"/><ref target="#entry_on"/><ref target="#entry_kom"/></xr> и др.), относится к старому иранскому фонду: <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>arm</w></mentioned> (в литературе не засвидетельствовано), <mentioned xml:lang="zza"><lang/><w>ärmä</w><gloss><q>плечо</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_KPF"><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Abt. III, Bd. IV, стр. 280</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">Abt. III, Bd. IV, p. 280</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="wbl"><lang/><w>yurm</w><gloss><q>рука</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ydg"><lang/><w>yārmё</w></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_Morgenstierne._IIFL"><biblScope>II 59</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="tly"><lang/><w>ām</w><gloss><q>плечо</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="tly"><w/><gloss><q>предплечье</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="sog"><lang/><w>*arm(’rm)</w></mentioned> в <mentioned xml:lang="sog"><lang/><w>’ps’rm</w><gloss><q>имеющий связанные за спиной руки</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_Gramm._sogd."><biblScope>II 90</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>er-</w><gloss><q>рука</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_BSOS"><biblScope>X 585</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>arəma-</w><gloss><q>рука</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>īrmа́-</w><gloss><q>рука</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="xcl"><lang/><w>armukn</w><gloss><q>локоть</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cu"><lang/><w>рамо</w><gloss><q>плечо</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="prg"><lang/><w>irmo</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="got"><lang/><w>arms</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/><w>Arm</w><gloss><q>рука</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/><w>armus</w><gloss><q>лопатка</q></gloss></mentioned>. В значении ‘оглобля’ — <mentioned xml:lang="lt"><lang/><w>armai</w></mentioned>. Для истории осетинского языка представляет интерес, что понятия ‘рука’, ‘нога’, ‘рот’ имеют наряду с иранскими наименованиями (%iarm%i, <xr><ref target="#entry_fad"/><ref target="#entry_kom"/></xr>) параллельный ряд неиранских, идущих из кавказского субстрата (<xr><ref target="#entry_kʼūx"/><ref target="#entry_kʼax"/><ref target="#entry_ʒyx"/></xr>), причем последние в самостоятельном употреблении почти вытеснили первые, тогда как в старых сложных словах и сочетаниях встречаются почти исключительно первые (иранские).%n<bibl corresp="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"><biblScope>II 50</biblScope></bibl>; <bibl corresp="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."><biblScope>35</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl corresp="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."><biblScope>24</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>17, 78, 117, 154, 197</biblScope></bibl>.</etym><etym xml:lang="en">Like most anatomical terms (see <xr><ref target="#entry_aǧd"/><ref target="#entry_cong"/><ref target="#entry_fad"/><ref target="#entry_zæng"/><ref target="#entry_zonyg"/><ref target="#entry_bazyg"/><ref target="#entry_wæxsk"/><ref target="#entry_on"/><ref target="#entry_kom"/></xr> etc.), it belongs to the old Iranian stock: <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>arm</w></mentioned> (not attested in literature), <mentioned xml:lang="zza"><lang/><w>ärmä</w><gloss><q>shoulder</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_KPF"><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Abt. III, Bd. IV, стр. 280</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">Abt. III, Bd. IV, p. 280</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="wbl"><lang/><w>yurm</w><gloss><q>hand</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ydg"><lang/><w>yārmё</w></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_Morgenstierne._IIFL"><biblScope>II 59</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="tly"><lang/><w>ām</w><gloss><q>shoulder</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="tly"><w/><gloss><q>forearm</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="sog"><lang/><w>*arm(’rm)</w></mentioned> in <mentioned xml:lang="sog"><lang/><w>’ps’rm</w><gloss><q>with the hands tied behind</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_Gramm._sogd."><biblScope>II 90</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>er-</w><gloss><q>hand</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl corresp="#ref_BSOS"><biblScope>X 585</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>arəma-</w><gloss><q>hand</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>īrmа́-</w><gloss><q>hand</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="xcl"><lang/><w>armukn</w><gloss><q>elbow</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cu"><lang/><w>рамо</w><gloss><q>shoulder</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="prg"><lang/><w>irmo</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="got"><lang/><w>arms</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/><w>Arm</w><gloss><q>hand</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/><w>armus</w><gloss><q>shoulder-blade</q></gloss></mentioned>. As for the meaning ‘shaft’, see <mentioned xml:lang="lt"><lang/><w>armai</w></mentioned>. For the history of Ossetic, it is of interest that the concepts ‘hand’, ‘leg’, ‘mouth’, along with Iranian names (%iarm%i, <xr><ref target="#entry_fad"/><ref target="#entry_kom"/></xr>) have a parallel row of non-Iranian words coming from the Caucasian substratum (<xr><ref target="#entry_kʼūx"/><ref target="#entry_kʼax"/><ref target="#entry_ʒyx"/></xr>), and the latter words almost forced out the former words in independent use, while in the old compound words and collocations there are almost exclusively the first (Iranian) words.%n<bibl corresp="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"><biblScope>II 50</biblScope></bibl>; <bibl corresp="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."><biblScope>35</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl corresp="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."><biblScope>24</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl corresp="#ref_ОЯФ_I"><biblScope>17, 78, 117, 154, 197</biblScope></bibl>.</etym></entry>